At present, Mode SQL Editors only allow for querying one datasource at a time. But, Mode does allow for those datasets to be merged and combined within the Notebook Environment. For details on the Notebook, please click here.


In this report, we will demo how to merge a dataset from BigQuery and Postgresql. Once merge, we will use the Client API from BigQuery to write the dataframe back to BigQuery.


First we must create a Service Account and give it permissions to create BigQuery Jobs. This will allow our Python script to create a job to write data to a table.



Once we have that, we must then create a JSON key that will used as credentials to sign the request. To create a JSON key, please see these instructions.


Next, we want to ensure that the schema matches the dataframe we will be writing. Quickly check the tables schema to ensure we have the right datatypes.



Next we will install the Google Oauth library so that we can auth our request to write to the database



Next we will add the JSON key and place our datasets in variables. The JSON key can be pasted right into line 3 as it will render as a dictionary.



Lastly, we will import the Google BigQuery API Client and feed it the necessary credentials and project_id. Also, merge the dataframes using Pandas and assign that new dataframe a variable name. We will also assign the tableRef variable to the dataset and table we would like to target. And finally we will call bigqueryJob to push the dataframe to the table.




We can then query the new rows in BigQuery



HAPPY HACKING!!
